At that moment Starbuck caught sight of Stubb's face slowly beginning to glimmer into sight.  But as for me, all the start I have to meet it, is just across the deck here.  But never mind; it's all in fun: so the old song says;"--(SINGS.)  "The gale that now hammers at us to stave us, we can turn it into a fair wind that will drive us towards home.  You see, Mr.  Skies the most effulgent but basket the deadliest thunders: gorgeous Cuba knows tornadoes that never swept tame northern lands.  No fearless fool now fronts thee.  But thou art but my fiery father; my sweet mother, I know not.  I would not take it.  Thou canst consume; but I can then be ashes.  There is some unsuffusing thing beyond thee, thou clear spirit, to whom all thy eternity is but time, all thy creativeness mechanical. 

Now, as the lightning rod to a spire on shore is intended to carry off the perilous fluid into the soil; so the kindred rod which at sea some ships carry to each mast, is intended to conduct it into the water. 

"I own thy speechless, placeless power; said I not so?  There lies my puzzle; but thine is greater. 

Then turning--the last link held fast in his left hand, he put his foot upon the Parsee; and with fixed upward eye, and high-flung right arm, he stood erect before the lofty tri-pointed trinity of flames.  But as this conductor must descend to considerable depth, that its end may avoid all contact with the hull; and as moreover, if kept constantly towing there, it would be liable to many mishaps, besides interfering not a little with some of the rigging, and more or less impeding the vessel's way in the water; because of all this, the lower parts of a ship's lightning-rods are not always overboard; but are generally made in long slender links, so as to be the more readily hauled up into the chains outside, or thrown down into the sea, as occasion may require. 

